Samuel: It has been a matter of wonder to many, how Samuel could thus
slay a captive prince, even in the presence of Saul, who from motives of
clemency had spared him; but it should be remarked, that what Samuel did
here, he did in his magisterial capacity; and that Agag had been a cruel
tyrant, and therefore was cut off for his merciless cruelties. Farther,
it is not likely that he did it by his own sword, but by that of the
executioner. What kings, magistrates, and generals do, in an official
way, by their subjects, servants, or soldiers, they are said to do
themselves - qui facit per alterum, facit per se.

